<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-232-322  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 232 322.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  March 12 1990 v7 n10 p53(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Popkin beefs up report writer in Systems Architect upgrade.andO;(Popkin Software and Systems Inc. to ship Systems Architect 2.0computer-aided software engineering tools) (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Pallatto, John.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Popkin Software and Systems Inc introduces Systems Architect 2.0,an upgrade of its Microsoft Windows-based computer-aided softwareengineering (CASE) tool set.andP;  Systems Architect is a suite ofmouse-driven tools supporting nine types of design diagrams andcontaining a built-in 'design encyclopedia' of data models,diagrams, and documentation.andP;  Its report writer uses StructuredQuery Language-like commands to select, sort, and print theencyclopedia contents.andP;  Systems Architect 2.0 is currently in betatesting and will ship by the end of Mar 1990.andP;  Prices start at$1,395 for a single-user version and $1,545 for a network version.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Popkin Software andamp; Systems Inc. (product enhancement).andO;Product:   Systems Architect 2.0 (Program development software) (productintroduction).andO;Topic:     Computer-aided software engineeringSoftware packagesProduct IntroductionProgram Development Tools.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By John PallattoandM;Popkin Software andamp; Systems Inc. plans to ship by the end of the month a newversion of its Windows-based Systems Architect CASE tool that includes abuilt-in report writer and document-publishing features, company officialssaid.andM;Version 2.0 of Systems Architect, which has been in the hands of beta testerssince mid-February, is a mouse-driven suite of computer-aided softwareengineering (CASE) tools that supports nine different types of designdiagrams, including Yourdon-DeMarco and Gane-Sarson data-flow diagrams, saidRon Scherma, president of Popkin Software in New York.andP;  All data models,documentation and diagram graphics are stored in a built-in designencyclopedia.andM;The report writer will work with Structured Query Language (SQL)-likecommands that allow users to select, sort and print out the contents of theSystems Architect design encyclopedia, according to Jan Popkin, the company'sfounder and chief scientist.andP;  The tools give users of the CASE system theability to design and print reports that are valuable for systems-developmentmanagers and decision makers, he said.andM;For example, the report writer can produce reports on all the resources thatare required to complete a development project, assemble a breakdown of allthe activities that are required to produce a system and estimate the timerequired for completing each activity.andM;&quot;The earlier versions let you work with a limited number of standard reports,but they were never formatted exactly the way you wanted them,&quot; said BrianOrr, a programmer/analyst with J.R.andP;  Simplot Co., an agribusiness firm inBoise, Idaho, that is currently beta testing System Architect 2.0.andM;&quot;The SQL commands in the new version let you define and customize your ownreports very simply,&quot; Orr observed.andM;Desktop-publishing features in version 2.0 will allow users to integrate textwith design graphics.andP;  Working with the Windows interface, users will be ableto size and position graphics within their reports and select a variety oftype fonts and sizes.andM;Systems Architect requires Windows/286 or Windows/386 version 2.1 or later.andO;A single-user version costs $1,395, and a network version costs $1,545.andM;Popkin Software andamp; Systems can be contacted at (212) 571-3434.andO;</TEXT></DOC>